    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nWhen using typed-`memoryview`s that are byte strings, would like to use the `.decode(...)` method on them to turn them into Python `str`s directly.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nHere is some simplified code that shows the intended behavior\n\n```cython\ncpdef str to_str(const unsigned char[::1] mv):\n    cdef str s = mv.decode(\"utf8\")\n    return s\n```\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\nCurrently one could work around this by accessing the pointer from the typed-`memoryview` and then assign it to `bytes`. This will then perform a C-string copy construction of the `bytes` object\n\n```cython\ncpdef str to_str(const unsigned char[::1] mv):\n    cdef const unsigned char* p = &mv[0]\n    cdef str s = p.decode(\"utf8\")\n    return s\n```\n\nHowever this comes with a few pitfalls:\n\n1. `strlen` is used to determine the length when the length is already known\n2. If the string is not `\\0` terminated, this would have undefined behavior and/or crash.\n\n<hr>\n\nOne could alternatively call `PyUnicode_Decode` this with the pointer and size from the object. While this always possible (even with the C-string), Cython already does a nice job of handling conversion to/from C-strings and various Python string objects. This just seems like a good common case that would be helpful to include.\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis can also be seen as an addendum to converting from typed-`memoryview`s to `bytes`:\n\n* https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7583",
